"{\"content\":{\"body\":\"**Friedrich August von Hayek** [CH](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Companion_of_Honour) [FBA](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellow_of_the_British_Academy) ([/ˈhaɪək/](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA/English) *[HY-ək](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Pronunciation_respelling_key)*, German: [\\\\[ˈfʁiːdʁɪç ˈʔaʊɡʊst fɔn ˈhaɪɛk\\\\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA/Standard_German) ([listen](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/02/Yandexhayek.wav)); 8 May 1899 – 23 March 1992), often referred to by his initials **F. A. Hayek**, was an Austrian-British [economist](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economist), and [philosopher](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosopher) who is best known for his defence of [classical liberalism](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_liberalism).[\\\\[1\\\\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-1) Hayek shared the 1974 [Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nobel_Memorial_Prize_in_Economic_Sciences) with [Gunnar Myrdal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gunnar_Myrdal) for their work on money and economic fluctuations, and the interdependence of economic, social and institutional phenomena.[\\\\[2\\\\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-:2-2) His account of how [changing prices communicate information](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Price_signal) that helps individuals coordinate their plans is widely regarded as an important achievement in [economics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economics), leading to his prize.[\\\\[3\\\\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-3)[\\\\[4\\\\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-4)[\\\\[5\\\\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-5)\\n\\nHayek served in [World War I](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_War_I) during his teenage years and said that this experience in the war and his desire to help avoid the mistakes that had led to the war drew him into economics.[\\\\[6\\\\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-:0-6)[\\\\[7\\\\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-7) At the [University of Vienna](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Vienna), he studied economics, eventually receiving his doctoral degrees in law in 1921 and in political science in 1923.[\\\\[6\\\\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-:0-6)[\\\\[8\\\\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-8) He subsequently lived and worked in Austria, Great Britain, the United States, and Germany; he became a British subject in 1938.[\\\\[9\\\\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-:3-9) Hayek's academic life was mostly spent at the [London School of Economics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/London_School_of_Economics), and later at the [University of Chicago](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Chicago), and the [University of Freiburg](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Freiburg). Although he is widely considered a leader of the [Austrian School of Economics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Austrian_School_of_Economics), he also had close connections with the [Chicago School of Economics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicago_School_of_Economics).[\\\\[6\\\\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-:0-6)[\\\\[10\\\\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-10)[\\\\[11\\\\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-11)[\\\\[12\\\\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-:4-12) Hayek was also a major social theorist and political philosopher of the 20th century and as the co-founder of [Mont Pelerin Society](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mont_Pelerin_Society) he contributed to the revival of classical liberalism in the post-war era.[\\\\[13\\\\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-13) His most popular work, *[The Road to Serfdom](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Road_to_Serfdom)*, has sold over 2.25 million copies (as of 2020).[\\\\[14\\\\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-14)[\\\\[15\\\\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-:1-15)\\n\\nHayek was appointed a [Co](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Order_of_the_Companions_of_Honour)\",\"timestamp\":1642726977,\"title\":\"Friedrich Hayek\"},\"digest\":\"TMafocEvnq3ssDwuYiBYYKf2kBhxF7zfGpsr411VB5s\",\"authorship\":{\"contributor\":\"0x2DCe50eDA07A869bb231595Faf881794154cc58E\",\"signingKey\":\"{\\\"crv\\\":\\\"P-256\\\",\\\"ext\\\":true,\\\"key_ops\\\":[\\\"verify\\\"],\\\"kty\\\":\\\"EC\\\",\\\"x\\\":\\\"IsNvsdvGB47Nn7p4pIos_V1McmaMTVKFTaUuLXiADxU\\\",\\\"y\\\":\\\"5ZmF2eNVSTc6lUao84vhafNJuZI4_18zcaNgIxeCAL8\\\"}\",\"signature\":\"E_QTzXT6Pd-jMur6FqMjDLyHDheXFQSyrh7UlxD-sL0AqjlFkLvnd0doA6fLJNiWbJ_1SQxSon7iAFyU96NMbg\",\"signingKeySignature\":\"0x90c67fdc538c922770cce43875dce7feaf27307737b8fac87fb282b496b4f8824d7bece0f2dcf8a026182d020f9196303b72314dbebf6923a944b749a3926ab01c\",\"signingKeyMessage\":\"I authorize publishing on mirror.xyz from this device using:\\n{\\\"crv\\\":\\\"P-256\\\",\\\"ext\\\":true,\\\"key_ops\\\":[\\\"verify\\\"],\\\"kty\\\":\\\"EC\\\",\\\"x\\\":\\\"IsNvsdvGB47Nn7p4pIos_V1McmaMTVKFTaUuLXiADxU\\\",\\\"y\\\":\\\"5ZmF2eNVSTc6lUao84vhafNJuZI4_18zcaNgIxeCAL8\\\"}\",\"algorithm\":{\"name\":\"ECDSA\",\"hash\":\"SHA-256\"}},\"nft\":{},\"version\":\"12-21-2020\",\"originalDigest\":\"TMafocEvnq3ssDwuYiBYYKf2kBhxF7zfGpsr411VB5s\"}"